{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The resemblance thesis is a crucial premise in Berkeley ' s argument from the ' likeness principle ' in §8 of the Principles .",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Yet, like the ' likeness principle ' , the resemblance thesis remains unargued for and is never explicitly defended.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "We provide a contextual answer to this question, focusing on epistemological discussions concerning resemblance and representation in Early Modern Irish Philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Ultimately, we conclude that Berkeley ' s acceptance of the resemblance thesis can be explained by the Irish intellectual climate in which he was writing.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Berkeley requires his readers to accept that ' for one thing to represent another, those two things must resemble one another ' .",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Various attempts have been made to explain why Berkeley accepts the resemblance thesis and why he fails to provide an explicit case for its defence.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Our aim is not to undermine Hill ' s reading and we do not contest the claim that Cartesian thought influenced Berkeley ' s philosophy -on the contrary, Berkeley ' s De Motu clearly suggests that Berkeley was influenced by Cartesianism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Ultimately, we conclude that Berkeley ' s views on the relation between representation and resemblance were influenced by the immediate Irish context in which he was writing and that this has so far been underappreciated in the relevant scholarship.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Our contention is that Molyneux ' s problem of the ' blind man made to see ' , and early responses to it, make it evident that the resemblance thesis was an underlying and often implicitly accepted principle in Irish thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Firstly, we argue that early responses to Molyneux ' s problem of a blind man made to see established the resemblance thesis as an underlying principle in Early Modern Irish philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "King draws on Molyneux ' s example, arguing we are no more familiar with God ' s attributes than a blind man is with the objects of sight.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Despite their disagreement, we emphasise that neither disputes the plausibility of the resemblance thesis itself.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Finally, we point to the fact that Berkeley uses Molyneux ' s original problem to defend his claim that the objects of touch and sight are fundamentally heterogenous (i.e., unalike) as further evidence that his acceptance of the resemblance thesis is rooted in Irish thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Berkeley himself uses the term ' represent ' in both a strict and a loose sense.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "By attributing the resemblance thesis to Berkeley, then, we take him to accept that representation, in this strict sense, requires resemblance.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "At least two passages make it clear that Berkeley both accepts the resemblance thesis and takes his opponents to accept it too.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Berkeley claims the key difference between (i) words and their objects, and (ii) ideas and their objects is that a word can arbitrarily signify any idea, without resembling it, while ideas themselves can only represent that which they resemble.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "In §8 of the Principles, the resemblance thesis clearly informs both Berkeley ' s characterisation of his opponents ' view and his response to that view.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Berkeley does not consider any other way in which an idea might represent its object beyond resemblance.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Hill provides such a reading, charting the rise of the resemblance thesis after Descartes -for whom, ' resemblance and causation cannot be separated ' -through later Cartesians such as Foucher, Du Hamel, and Malebranche.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Our claim, however, is that it would be amiss not to also consider Berkeley ' s immediate, local context -in Ireland.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Molyneux ' s answer is no.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Our contention is that there is an implicit principle at work here; namely, the resemblance thesis.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "King uses the man born blind to illustrate his point that we have no proper notion of God and his attributes.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "King argues that there need only be a ' faint resemblance ' or a ' little likeness ' , as he later puts it, between two things in order for one to represent the other.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "In short, Berkeley, like King, accepts the resemblance thesis and brings it to bear on the problem of divine attributes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "Berkeley agrees with King that human attributes can be considered as ' representations ' of their divine counterparts precisely because there is some resemblance between them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "Berkeley ' s claim, which he establishes over the course of the text, is that the constant connection that we perceive between certain visual experiences (e.g. seeing shapes with corners) and certain tangible experiences (e.g. the feeling of sharpness) is only a ' habitual connexion that experience has made us to observe between them ' (NTV, §147).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "Berkeley ' s usage of the man born blind clearly illustrates how his solution differs from King ' s.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU30": {
      "text": "We set out to explain Berkeley ' s acceptance of the resemblance thesis by placing his views concerning representation and resemblance in the context of debates that were happening in his immediate intellectual environment in Dublin and Ireland.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
